article.description: Shareef Abdur-Rahim will end his seventh season just like his first six -- out of the playoffs.
article.headline: Grizzlies have lost 10 of 12 games
article.linkText: Abdur-Rahim, Hawks play for pride yet again
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Shareef Abdur-Rahim will end his seventh season just like his first six -- out of the playoffs. Atlanta beat the Memphis Grizzlies 97-91 Saturday night, one day after Milwaukee's win over Cleveland eliminated the Hawks from playoff contention. Abdur-Rahim, who played his first five seasons in Vancouver, didn't hesitate when asked what will motivate the team for the rest of the season. "Just pride," he said. "Just pride. Just go out and do your job. That's all you can do is go out and do your job." Jason Terry scored 23 points and Dion Glover added 20 as Atlanta sent the Grizzlies to their seventh straight loss. The Hawks never trailed after Terry hit two free throws with 1:58 remaining in the first quarter, but the effort was too late to save the front office from giving their 2002-03 season-ticket holders a full refund. Management had decided before the season to refund season-ticket holders if the Hawks failed to make the postseason for the fourth straight year. Pau Gasol had 25 points and 13 rebounds to lead Memphis, which has lost 10 of 12 after a 7-1 stretch last month. The Grizzlies, one night after blowing a 23-point fourth-quarter lead at home and losing to the Los Angeles Lakers, made a 15-3 run in the fourth quarter to close within 93-85 after Gasol hit a 3-foot leaner with 3:29 left. "They got a lot of fast-break points," Gasol said. "We could never stop that. We let them run. We were not getting back." Memphis outscored Atlanta 27-14 in the fourth quarter, but Brevin Knight missed three jumpers down the stretch. Knight replaced Jason Williams midway through the third quarter as the Grizzlies' point guards combined to shoot 1-for-14 from the floor. "For us, the way we played in the fourth quarter is how we played last night defensively," Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. "Unfortunately for us, we just let it get away on us in the third quarter." Terry and the Hawks took advantage of Memphis' struggles and pushed the ball up the court. "We're a transition team," Terry said. "When we get the running game going like we did tonight, we are very dangerous." Abdur-Rahim, who had 19 points and seven rebounds, followed Ira Newble's missed layup to give the Hawks their biggest lead at 71-50. Reserve forward Earl Watson added 17 points for Memphis. "We just didn't have enough time on the clock to come back and get over the hump,'' Watson said. "We got it down a couple of times, but we couldn't hit some shots." Game notes
Hawks forward Glenn Robinson missed his second straight game with an inflamed left Achilles' tendon. ... The Grizzlies played most of the second half without starter Lorenzen Wright, who reinjured a sprained right thumb. Wright still managed eight points and 10 rebounds in 24 minutes. Brown said Wright might have torn ligaments, but added the medical staff won't know until Sunday. ... Memphis also was without guard Mike Miller, who has been slowed by back spasms that limited him to four minutes Friday.
